<XMLHttpRequestAbort_event>
<summary>
The <c>abort</c> event is fired when a request has been aborted, for example because the program called <see cref="XMLHttpRequest.Abort"/>.
</summary>
<remarks>
<para>-Related events: <see cref="XMLHttpRequest/loadstart_event"/>, <see cref="XMLHttpRequest/load_event"/>, <see cref="XMLHttpRequest/progress_event"/>, <see cref="XMLHttpRequest/error_event"/>, <see cref="XMLHttpRequest/loadend_event"/><br/>-<see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/XMLHttpRequest/Using_XMLHttpRequest#monitoring_progress">Monitoring progress</see><br/></para>
<para><seealso href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/XMLHttpRequest/abort_event"> <em>See also on MDN</em> </seealso></para>
</remarks>
</XMLHttpRequestAbort_event>
